<paragraph id="A81336C2FFBA2853FF4DFCF12A31A0A1" blockId="3.[151,1437,775,1520]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FF4DFCF12F02A031" box="[151,263,776,800]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Lectotype</typeStatus>
female (present designation): ZMHB: Casapava, Sello (green label)/ cotype (red label)/ 217 (white label)/ 1. (white label)/ 
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FE7AFCD42CC1A054" authority="Klug" authorityName=": Klug" authorityYear="1838" box="[416,708,812,837]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FE7AFCD42C81A054" box="[416,644,812,837]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Bittacus brasiliensis</emphasis>
Klug
</taxonomicName>
(white label). 
<materialsCitation id="18C43C9FFFBA2853FCB2FCD42A2AA0A1" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2029164528" country="Argentina" county="Missiones" location="High" municipality="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" specimenCount="4" typeStatus="lectotype">
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FCB2FCD42DDDA054" box="[872,984,813,837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Lectotype</typeStatus>
represented in figure 1b. There are now two 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FF12FCB62F68A079" box="[200,365,847,872]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">paralectotypes</typeStatus>
, both females deposited at ZMHB, with labels equal to the 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FBD7FCB62A76A079" box="[1037,1139,847,872]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">lectotype</typeStatus>
except by the small white label “1.”, present only in the 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FDD8FC8D2C68A09C" box="[514,621,884,909]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">lectotype</typeStatus>
. 
<location id="AD736019FFBA2853FDA6FC8D2CB1A09C" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:200587D4FFBA2853FF4DFDC52F5DA6E1:AD736019FFBA2853FDA6FC8D2CB1A09C" box="[636,692,884,909]" country="Argentina" county="Missiones" municipality="Rio Grande do Sul" name="High" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">High</location>
resolution images of the three specimens were examined here. 
<location id="AD736019FFBA2853FF4DFC6E2EE9A0A1" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:200587D4FFBA2853FF4DFDC52F5DA6E1:AD736019FFBA2853FF4DFC6E2EE9A0A1" box="[151,236,919,944]" country="Argentina" county="Missiones" municipality="Rio Grande do Sul" name="Species" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Species</location>
also known from 
<collectingMunicipality id="4877ACB8FFBA2853FE62FC6E2C8CA0A1" box="[440,649,919,944]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingMunicipality>
(
<figureCitation id="30972A47FFBA2853FD43FC6E2CFDA0A1" box="[665,760,919,944]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1494,1516]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,203,1473]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1435,193,1473]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distribution records of Bittacus species in Brazil. a) B. angrensis, B. aripuanensis, B. blancheti, B. brasiliensis, B. brunipennis; b) B. boraceiensis, B. cruzi sp. n., B. diversinervis, B. femoralis; c) B. ferreirai sp. n., B. flavescens, B. froehlichi, B. latreillei; d) B. maculosus, B. omega, B. pintoi, B. varzeanus sp. n. Bittacus geniculatus is not represented because of its imprecise location." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2611679/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Fig. 12a</figureCitation>
), and 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FCE6FC6E2DB5A0A1" box="[828,944,919,944]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Argentina</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingCounty id="41724E4EFFBA2853FC60FC6E2A2AA0A1" box="[954,1071,919,944]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Missiones</collectingCounty>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A81336C2FFBA2853FF1DFC442F5DA6E1" blockId="3.[151,1437,775,1520]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FF1DFC442FAFA0C4" authorityName=": Klug" authorityYear="1838" box="[199,426,956,981]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FF1DFC442FAFA0C4" box="[199,426,956,981]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Bittacus brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an enigmatic species, known only by the 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FC42FC442DCDA0C4" box="[920,968,957,981]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">type</typeStatus>
series from 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FB89FC452A92A0C4" box="[1107,1175,956,981]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and an additional male from 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FF0EFC262F41A0E9" box="[212,324,991,1016]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FE8BFC262FFBA0E9" author="Kimmins, D. E." box="[337,510,991,1016]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" pagination="403 - 405" refId="ref15203" refString="Kimmins, D. E. (1939) Nota sobre Bittacus braziliensis Klug (Mecoptera). Notas del Museo de La Plata, 27, 403 - 405." type="journal article" year="1939">Kimmins 1939</bibRefCitation>
). Its wing venation is distinctive (
<figureCitation id="30972A47FFBA2853FCAFFC262DC1A0E9" box="[885,964,991,1016]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1896,1918]" captionTargetBox="[153,1428,208,1870]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,195,1871]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Bittacus adult habitus images. a) B. angrensis; b) B. brasiliensis, lectotype; c) B. flavescens, holotype; d) B. geniculatus, holotype. Scale bars = 1 mm. Type specimen photos provided by Michael Ohl (ZMHB)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2611649/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
) from that of other Brazilian 
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FAD6FC182B6DA0E9" box="[1292,1384,993,1016]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FAD6FC182B6DA0E9" box="[1292,1384,993,1016]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Bittacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see identification key), so much so that the species was not included in 
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FC53FBFD2A04A70C" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1908" box="[905,1025,1028,1053]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Thyridates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FC53FBFD2A04A70C" box="[905,1025,1028,1053]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Thyridates</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FBF0FBFD2AEFA70D" author="Willmann, R." box="[1066,1258,1028,1053]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" pagination="47 - 65" refId="ref16394" refString="Willmann, R. (1983) Die phylogenetischen Beziehungen unter den sudamerikanischen Bittacidae (Insecta: Mecoptera). Zoologische Beitrage Neue Folge, 28, 47 - 65." type="journal article" year="1983">Willmann (1983)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FAFAFBFD2F49A751" author="Collucci, E. &amp; Amorim, D. S." pageId="3" pageNumber="306" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref14802" refString="Collucci, E. &amp; Amorim, D. S. (2000) Three new species of Thyridates Navas, 1908 (Mecoptera, Bittacidae) from Brazil, with new combinations and some comments about phylogenetic relationships within the genus. Contribuicoes Avulsas Sobre a Historia Natural do Brasil, Serie Zoologia, 21, 1 - 8." type="journal article" year="2000">Collucci &amp; Amorim (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. All of the 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FE17FBD12FF8A751" box="[461,509,1064,1088]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">type</typeStatus>
series specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FD30FBD02D8EA751" authorityName=": Klug" authorityYear="1838" box="[746,907,1063,1088]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FD30FBD02D8EA751" box="[746,907,1063,1088]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">B. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have labels mentioning only Cassapava as the 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FF4DFBB42EC2A774" box="[151,199,1101,1125]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">type</typeStatus>
locality, and Sellow as the collector (
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FDA7FBB52CF9A775" author="Klug, J. C. F." box="[637,764,1100,1125]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" pagination="81 - 108" refId="ref15234" refString="Klug, J. C. F. (1838) Versuch einer systematischen Feststellung der Insekten-Familie: Panorpatae und Auseinandersetzung ihrer Gattungen und Arten. Abhandlungen der koniglichen Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin, 1836, 81 - 108." type="journal article" year="1838">Klug 1838</bibRefCitation>
). Friedrich Sellow (or Sello) was a famous German insect collector who spent a long time in southern and southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FC99FB962D8EA799" box="[835,907,1135,1160]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. One of his most famous and longer campaigns (
<date id="DC121002FFBA2853FF45FB6D2F1AA7BC" box="[159,287,1172,1197]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" value="1823" valueMax="1826">1823–1826</date>
) was in 
<collectingRegion id="6A68F820FFBA2853FE53FB6D2C60A7BC" box="[393,613,1172,1197]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
state (RS), where he collected a large number of insects that were all shipped to Berlin (
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FEBFFB412C14A7C1" author="Papavero, N." box="[357,529,1208,1232]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" refId="ref15709" refString="Papavero, N. (1971) Essays on the history of Neotropical dipterology: with special references to collectors (1750 - 1905). Fol. I. Museu de Zoologia, Universidade de Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, 216 pp." type="book" year="1971">Papavero 1971</bibRefCitation>
). During his trips in 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FD2FFB4E2D39A7C1" box="[757,828,1207,1232]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Sellow recorded very extensive and detailed journals, where he mentioned several trips to Cassapava (RS) (
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FCC1FB252DC9A7E5" author="Papavero, N." box="[795,972,1244,1268]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" refId="ref15709" refString="Papavero, N. (1971) Essays on the history of Neotropical dipterology: with special references to collectors (1750 - 1905). Fol. I. Museu de Zoologia, Universidade de Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, 216 pp." type="book" year="1971">Papavero 1971</bibRefCitation>
), probably where the 
<typeStatus id="77178860FFBA2853FB0DFB242B02A7E4" box="[1239,1287,1245,1269]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">type</typeStatus>
series of 
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FA5EFB242F1DA609" authorityName=": Klug" authorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FA5EFB242F1DA609" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">B. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comes from. Cassapava (RS) corresponds today to the municipality of 
<collectingRegion id="6A68F820FFBA2853FB94FAF92B0BA609" box="[1102,1294,1279,1304]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Caçapava do Sul</collectingRegion>
located in a mountainous region in the central RS. The record of 
<taxonomicName id="6FAC4D41FFBA2853FD35FADC2D95A62C" authorityName=": Klug" authorityYear="1838" box="[751,912,1316,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="9AD8EAD0FFBA2853FD35FADC2D95A62C" box="[751,912,1316,1341]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">B. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FC0DFADD2A43A62C" box="[983,1094,1316,1341]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="6A68F820FFBA2853FB8CFADD2AC6A62C" box="[1110,1219,1316,1341]" country="Argentina" name="Misiones" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Misiones</collectingRegion>
: Loreto) (
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FAEBFADD2ED5A671" author="Kimmins, D. E." pageId="3" pageNumber="306" pagination="403 - 405" refId="ref15203" refString="Kimmins, D. E. (1939) Nota sobre Bittacus braziliensis Klug (Mecoptera). Notas del Museo de La Plata, 27, 403 - 405." type="journal article" year="1939">Kimmins 1939</bibRefCitation>
) reinforces the idea that the Brazilian specimens were also collected in the southernmost regions of 
<collectingCountry id="D0BB7652FFBA2853FA8BFABE2B9CA671" box="[1361,1433,1351,1376]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. This explanation is needed because the name Cassapava might generate some confusion, since another city located in the Atlantic rain forest in 
<collectingRegion id="6A68F820FFBA2853FE3AFA692C56A6B9" box="[480,595,1423,1448]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
state was also named Cassapava (known today as Caçapava). Sellow did spend some time collecting in 
<collectingRegion id="6A68F820FFBA2853FE31FA4D2C5EA6DC" box="[491,603,1460,1485]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="3" pageNumber="306">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
state, but there is no mention of Cassapava in his journals during that time (
<bibRefCitation id="CC3D4B33FFBA2853FF44FA212F4EA6E1" author="Papavero, N." box="[158,331,1496,1520]" pageId="3" pageNumber="306" refId="ref15709" refString="Papavero, N. (1971) Essays on the history of Neotropical dipterology: with special references to collectors (1750 - 1905). Fol. I. Museu de Zoologia, Universidade de Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, 216 pp." type="book" year="1971">Papavero 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
